{{Other uses|Sakka (disambiguation){{!}}Sakka}} {{Infobox settlement | name = Sakka | official_name = | native_name = سكا<!-- for cities whose native name is not in English --> | other_name = Saqqa | settlement_type = Village | image_skyline = | image_caption = | image_flag = | image_seal = | image_shield = | nickname = | motto = | image_map = | map_caption = | pushpin_map = Syria <!-- the name of a location map as per http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Location_map --> | pushpin_label_position = bottom | pushpin_mapsize = 250 | pushpin_map_caption = Location in Syria | coordinates = {{coord|33|26|0|N|36|27|22|E|region:SY|display=inline,title}} | subdivision_type = Country | subdivision_name = {{flag|Syria}} | subdivision_type1 = [[Governorates of Syria|Governorate]] | subdivision_name1 = [[Rif Dimashq Governorate]] | subdivision_type2 = [[Districts of Syria]] | subdivision_name2 = [[Douma District]] | subdivision_type3 = [[Nahiyah]] | subdivision_name3 = [[Al-Ghizlaniyah]] | subdivision_type4 = | subdivision_name4 = | established_title = <!-- Settled --> | established_date = | government_footnotes = | government_type = | leader_title = | leader_name = | area_footnotes = | area_total_km2 = <!-- ALL fields dealing with a measurements are subject to automatic unit conversion--> | area_land_km2 = <!--See table @ Template:Infobox Settlement for details on automatic unit conversion--> | area_water_km2 = | elevation_footnotes = <!--for references: use<ref> </ref> tags--> | elevation_m = | population_footnotes = | population_total = 1520 | population_as_of = 2004 census | population_density_km2 = | population_note = | timezone = [[Eastern European Time|EET]] | utc_offset = +2 | timezone_DST = [[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]] | utc_offset_DST = +3 | postal_code_type = <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... --> | postal_code = | area_code = | website = | footnotes = }}
'''Sakka''' or '''Saqqa''' ({{lang-ar|سكا}}) is a village to the southeast of [[Damascus]], on the edge of the [[Ghouta]], {{convert|5|km|mi}} north west of [[Damascus International Airport]] in [[Syria]].<ref name="Burns2005">{{cite book|author=Ross Burns|title=Damascus: A History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xTs77Ft6FXQC&pg=PA4|accessdate=21 September 2012|date=20 January 2005|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-0-415-27105-9|pages=4–}}</ref>
==Tell Sakka== '''Tell Sakka''' is a man-made [[Tell (archaeology)|tell]] in the neighborhood that has been excavated by [[Ahmed Taraqji]] on behalf of the [[Directorate-General of Antiquities and Museums]].<ref>Taraqji, A., "Nouvelles decouvertes sur les relations avec 1'Egypte a Tell Sakka et a Keswe, dans la region de Damas," Bulletin de la Societe Francaise d'Egyptologie 144:27-43, 1999.</ref>
Remains of a palace was found and dated to between 1800 and 1600 BCE. It has provided evidence of Egyptian influence in the Ghouta,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.louvre.fr/12h30tell-sakka-une-ville-du-bronze-moyen-de-damascene-1800-1600-syrie|title= à 12h30Tell Sakka, une ville du Bronze Moyen de Damascène (1800-1600), Syrie|publisher= louvre|date= |accessdate=8 April 2015}}</ref> The architectural remains were said to resemble those of [[Qatna]] and along with [[pottery]] were dated to the [[Middle Bronze Age]].<ref>[http://www.akademiai.com/content/l99217ww251u5k80/ E. H. Bakraji, M. Ahmad, N. Salman, D. Haloum, N. Boutros, R. Abboud., Dating and classification of Syrian excavated pottery from Tell Saka Site, by means of thermoluminescence analysis, and multivariate statistical methods, based on PIXE analysis, Journal of Radioanalytical and Nuclear Chemistry, Akadémiai Kiadó, co-published with Springer Science+Business Media B.V., 1999]</ref> A [[courtyard]] was excavated measuring {{convert|14.5|m|ft}} by {{convert|22.5|m|ft}}. Columns marked the entrance to the south and four large columns were positioned in a square in the centre of the courtyard. [[Tempera]]<ref name="BietakCzerny2007">{{cite book|author1=Manfred Bietak|author2=Ernst Czerny|author3=Österreichische Akademie der Wissenschaften|title=The synchronisation of civilisations in the Eastern Mediterranean in the second millennium B.C.: proceedings of the SCIEM 2000-2nd EuroConference Vienna, 28th of May-1st of June 2003|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nN8TAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=21 September 2012|year=2007|publisher=Verlag der Österreichischen Akademie der Wissenschaften|isbn=978-3-7001-3527-2}}</ref> or perhaps [[Fresco]] technique Paintings were found on the walls showing ancient Egyptian style and motifs.<ref name="HeinzFeldman2007">{{cite book|author1=Marlies Heinz|author2=Marian H. Feldman|title=Representations of Political Power: Case Histories from Times of Change and Dissolving Order in the Ancient Near East|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_7kP_hNKHxIC&pg=PA51|accessdate=21 September 2012|year=2007|publisher=Eisenbrauns|isbn=978-1-57506-135-1|pages=51–}}</ref> However, beneath the apparent Egyptian scheme, a Near-Eastern tradition is evident in the ideas of the paintings.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=gr5BgOwEJicC&pg=PA129#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Beyond Babylon: Art, Trade, and Diplomacy in the Second Millennium B.C.|author1=Joan Aruz |author2=Kim Benzel |author3=Jean M. Evans |page= 129|year= 2008}}</ref>
The first [[cuneiform]] tablet recovered in the Damascus area was found at Tell Sakka. It was suggested resemble the style of cuneiform found in the archives of [[Mari, Syria|Mari]] and speaks of a king called [[Zimri-Lim]]. The cuneiform tablet in Sakka was translated to read ''"To my brother Zimri-lim, say "Thus saith Kanhilesu? Your brothers Samas and Dagan for the rest of the days, My brother sustenance? In front of me (it is) good. In front of my brother that is well! I heard: The enemy of my country brother, My brother has attacked, news of him that sent me! (...) inside a (?) [..., The army [of my country?], to my brother [(go go)]."''<ref>[http://www.damascusuniversity.edu.sy/mag/human/images/stories/31-34.pdf Abdallah, Fayssal., La Découverte d'un Premier Texte Cunéiforme A Damas, Tell Sakka, Revision Historique, Damascus University Journal, Vol. 27, No. 3+4, 2011.]</ref>
Other finds at the site included a [[sphinx]] made out of the [[scapula]] of a [[cow]].<ref>[http://www.naturalsciences.be/common/pdf/science/aswa2011/aswa2011_abstracts.pdf al Besso, Moussab., Production d'objets en os dans un atelier du Bronze Moyen en Syrie du Sud: Tell Sakka, Paper for the 10th International Archaeozoology of Southwestern Asia and Adjacent Areas, Brussels, June 28th-30th, 2011.]{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
